'''''Boletus regius''''', commonly known as the '''royal bolete''' or '''red-capped butter bolete''', is a [[basidiomycota|basidiomycete]] [[fungus]] of the [[genus]] ''[[Boletus]]'' found in China, Europe, and North America.  ''B.&nbsp;regius'' has a pink cap, yellow [[trama (mycology)|flesh]], and a reticulate pattern on the [[stipe (mycology)|stem]].<ref name=bolcom/>  [[Harry D. Thiers]] described a similar mushroom from [[California]] as ''B.&nbsp;regius'',<ref name=thiers75/> although it has yet to be shown to be the same species. ''B.&nbsp;regius'' in Europe does not stain when exposed to air,<ref name=bolcom/> or stains weakly,<ref name="Ellis 1990"/> but the California species stains blue.<ref name="Bessette 2000"/> Both European and California specimens are considered choice [[edible mushroom|edibles]].<ref name=mykoweb/>

==Taxonomy==
The species was first described and illustrated by [[Julius Vincenz von Krombholz]] in 1832.<ref name="von Krombholz 1832"/> [[Common name]]s for the mushroom include the red-capped butter bolete<ref name="Bessette 2000"/> and the royal bolete.<ref name="BMS"/>

In the genus ''Boletus'', ''B.&nbsp;auripes'' is [[classification (biology)|classified]] as a member of the [[section (biology)|section]] ''Appendiculati''. Species in this section are characterized by having a dry cap with a surface texture ranging from smooth to somewhat [[wikt:tomentose|tomentose]], yellow [[trama (mycology)|flesh]], a reticulate stem, and a mild taste. Other North American boletes of ''Appendiculati'' include ''[[Boletus speciosus]]'' and ''[[Boletus auripes]]''.<ref name="Snell 1970"/>

==Description==
[[File:2008-12-09 Boletus regius 1 15136.jpg|thumb|left|''Boletus regius'' [[sensu]] Thiers, collected in California]]
The [[basidiocarp|fruit bodies]] of ''Boletus regius'' have [[pileus (mycology)|caps]] that are initially convex before flattening out in maturity, reaching a diameter of {{convert|7|<U+2013>|20|cm|in|abbr=on}} wide. The cap surface is pink to red, occasionally with hints of yellow or brown, more so around the margin. Initially velvety to slightly [[tomentum|tomentose]] (hairy) when young, these minute hairs tend to slough off with age, and the cap develops wrinkles and pits. The cap [[trama (mycology)|flesh]] is yellow, and slowly and erratically bruises blue in North American specimens. The pores on the underside of the cap are angular, and measure about 1<U+2013>2 per millimetre. The color of the pore surface is bright yellow to start, but eventually darkens somewhat, and will stain blue with damage. The depth of the tubes comprising the pores extends to {{convert|0.8|<U+2013>|2.5|cm|in|1|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Bessette 2000"/>

The [[stipe (mycology)|stem]] measures {{convert|5|<U+2013>|13|cm|in|abbr=on}} long by {{convert|2.5|<U+2013>|5|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} thick, and typically has a thick, bulbous base. It is solid (i.e., not hollow), and a bright yellow color, often with reddish tones, particularly near the base of the stem. The stem surface can be covered with fine yellow reticulations either throughout its length, or just on the upper portion. ''Boletus regius'' produces an olive-brown [[spore print]]. Its smooth, [[hyaline]] (translucent) [[spore]]s are roughly elliptical to somewhat [[wikt:fusoid|fusoid]] (wider in the middle and tapering toward the ends) to more or less cylindrical, and have dimensions of 12<U+2013>17 by 4<U+2013>5&nbsp;[[micrometre|<U+03BC>m]].<ref name="Bessette 2000"/>

[[Chemical tests in mushroom identification|Chemical tests]] can be used to help identify ''Boletus regius'' in the field. The [[cap cuticle]] will stain a pale purple color if [[Iron(II) sulfate|FeSO<sub>4</sub>]] is applied; this same test will turn the flesh grayish.<ref name="Bessette 2000"/>

==Habitat and distribution==
''Boletus regius'' is an ecto[[mycorrhiza]]l species with a broad [[host (biology)|host]] range,<ref name="Smith 2008"/> and associates with [[oak]] and [[conifer]]s, particularly [[fir]]. Fruit bodies grow on the grow singly, scattered about, or grouped together. In North America, they usually appear from August to November, although they also appear between May and June. The North American distribution includes the [[Pacific Northwest]] states [[California]], [[Oregon]], and [[Washington]], where its frequency of occurrence ranges from "rare to locally abundant".<ref name="Bessette 2000"/> It is rare in Europe, and appears on the [[Regional Red List]] of several countries.<ref name="Koune 2001"/> The species was also been recorded from China.<ref name="Chiu 1948"/>

